snippet: Dutch voters appeared to give Prime Minister Mark Rutte a narrow victory, which will bring a sigh of relief to European allies anxious about rising euro skepticism in the richer countries of the north.
abstract: Dutch voters appear to give Prime Minister Mark Rutte a narrow victory, which will bring a sigh of relief to European allies anxious about rising euro skepticism in the richer countries of the north; Rutte’s party won 41 seats out of the 150 at stake, and Labor, led by a fresh-faced leader, Diederik Samsom, won 40; vote would make a governing coalition of the two parties possible, but negotiations will be difficult.
lead_paragraph: Dutch voters appeared to give Prime Minister Mark Rutte a narrow victory, which will bring a sigh of relief to European allies anxious about rising euro skepticism in the richer countries of the north.

headline.main: Support for the Euro Is Seen in Dutch Election Results
